05489nam a22006855i 9780774867412DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748674127 a10.59962/97807748674122doi  a(DE-B1597)661646  a(OCoLC)1328135226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLAW0380002bisacsh04a346.71015qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aHouse Rules :bChanging Families, Evolving Norms, and the Role of the Law /ced. by Régine Tremblay, Erez Aloni. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLocating Norms -- tThe Private Lives of High-Wealth Families -- tIdentity Choices at the Intersections -- tLaw’s Norms -- tFamily Law as Expression -- tThe Complex Interrelationships of Financial and Child-Related Issues in Post-separation Disputes -- tNorms’ Stickiness -- tFamilial Ideology, Privatization, and Care Arrangements for Children in the Family Law and Child Protection Systems -- tFamily, Gender, and the Public/Private Divide in the United Kingdom’s Human Rights Act 1998 -- tMeasuring Norms -- tOne Myth Leads to Another -- t“WAR” and Other Reasons People Move In Together -- tReforming Norms -- tMeasuring Success of (Family) Law Reforms -- tAbolishing Family Law (as We Know It) -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe paradigm of family has shifted rapidly and dramatically, from nuclear unit to diverse constellations of intimacy. At the same time, some norms resist change, such as women’s continuing role as primary care providers despite their increased uptake of paid work. This tension between transformation and stasis in family arrangements has an impact on economic, emotional, and legal aspects of daily life. House Rules critically explores the intertwining of norms and laws that govern familial relationships. The authors in this incisive collection engage with four countries – Canada, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Taiwan – and expose the ingrained and unsettled norms that affect families and the law’s role in regulating them. Over recent decades, the law has struggled to adjust to transformations in what typifies the structures and practices of family life. House Rules provides tools to analyze those difficulties and, ultimately, to design laws to better respond to ongoing change and avoid entrenching inequalities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Family Law / General.2bisacsh1 aAloni, Erez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAloni, Erez, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarker, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelleau, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Chao-ju, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCossman, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiduck, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvanyi, Julianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTait, Allison Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreloar, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTremblay, Régine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTremblay, Régine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVanzella-Yang, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWieg